		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
NamelessArchon wrote:<BR>
<P>First, let's lay out the problems I see with the LDoN expansion: </P>
<P>1. Point awards are stingy in the extreme. A new player (15-20) doing LDoN adventures will be rewarded with one or two (1 or 2) points, half that if they take 120 minutes instead of 90. A level 65 player will receive ~50. At this rate, the level 65 player will require 200+ missions to purchase their 1492 gear. (1492points * 7items = 10444points for all items, 10444points / 50points per adventure = 209 adventures) The level 15 neophyte will long have outlevelled the gear they were desiring to purchase before they can afford it - this is particularly true of spells.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>My thoughts EXACTLY!! Should be 1-3 missions to get 1 piece of gear.</FONT></P>
<P>Please note that this does NOT include any augmentations, or any equipment for any non-visable slots. This is only for (head, robe, legs, arms, wrists (x2), hands) and does not include LDoN shoulders, rings, ears, belts, and so forth. This is approximately 30 (thirty) adventures to get ONE piece of gear, and assumes NO failures or partial failures (120 minute adventures).</P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>Should be same as gear, 1-3 wins to get an augment.</FONT></P>
<P>2. Points are not tradeable. No player can accrue points for others, donate their points for friends, or purchase gear for others to use. No collectives, guilds, traders, or bargainers may benefit from repeated LDoN adventures, unless the reward is something that they themselves need. This means that LDoN gear exists completely outside the commodity/economic market of Everquest. While this might be useful for the establishment of a "baseline" set of equipment available to all, the time investment needed to acquire such a "baseline set" (see point #1) is prohibitive in the extreme.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>Sellable/tradeable points like DON crystals is the way to go here. Many players have unused points with nothing to spend them on.</FONT></P>
<P>3. Gear is notably inferior to recent content items, including those of the (far) superior DoN task system. It was designed to be slightly "behind the curve" at the time the expansion was released (sub-elemental when fully aug'd, when elemental gear was not top of the line) and has aged very poorly in accordance with this. The gear relies on various augmentations that are usable only in LDoN equipment in order to approach anything a player would not be embarrassed to be using. </P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>Convert&nbsp;old LDON gear/points into DON crystals/faction tokens would help with getting started on DON.</FONT></P>
<P>How would I fix this? Pick your poisons - not all of these will work out of the box and unmodified. Do not apply all at the same time (1 and 2, for example)</P>
<P>Some ideas:<BR></P>
<OL>
<LI>Rebalance point costs. An item designed to be used by a level 20 player should cost no more than the number of points that player can accrue in three to six missions - somewhere between 3 and 18. This means that the costs for the current 1492 armor should be approximately 150 to 300 points each, and that the entire set should be available to a player that has performed between 21 and 35 missions. Please note - as above, this calculation does NOT include ANY augmentations or non-visable slots.</LI></OL>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT color=#ffff00>With over 2000 items to change point values on, seems like a lot of work </FONT><FONT color=#ffff00>when its easier to change points awarded.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; DON&nbsp;only needs like 2-4&nbsp;missions to get 1 piece of gear.</FONT></P>
<P><BR></P>
<OL>
<LI>Rebalance point awards. Simply multiply all current awards by a factor of six to ten. The level 65 player will receive 300 to 500 points per mission, and be able to acquire their gear as above in three to five adventures per piece. Please note, as above, this does not include any "extras", only the listed slots filled with the 1492 gear.</LI></OL>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<FONT color=#ffff00>&nbsp; Still the fastest way to start on a LDON revamp!!!&nbsp;&nbsp; I'm greedy multipy by 15-30 <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0> A level 65 should get closer to&nbsp; 1200 points, closer to getting ONE (1) piece of top of the line 1492 gear!!! A level 20 should get 20-30 points per win, </FONT><FONT color=#ffff00>closer to getting the antitrap spells or the 150 point gear. Every 7 levels the mobs get harder so more points earned is a good thing!!!<BR></FONT></P>
<OL>
<LI>Adjust statistics of LDoN items. This would work, but could be exceedingly labor intensive - if the point is to balance LDoN risk-versus-reward ratio, however, this must be considered. In particular, augmentation slots should certainly be revisited - there are many augments that will function only in LDoN gear, and many pieces of equipment that can use primarily only LDoN augments. </LI></OL>
<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <FONT color=#ffff00>More gear&nbsp;with LDON type 2/3 slots would also help here....tradeskilled gear like old cultural (2 extra type 2/3 slots), new cultural( trade the type 12 for a type 2/3, there are very few type 12 augments), LDON crafted gear like Gothic (1&nbsp;type&nbsp;2/3 slots)-Whats a type 1 augment anyway??, newbie quested armor&nbsp;(an extra&nbsp;type&nbsp;2/3 slot on chest and legs),&nbsp;Velious/God/OOW quested armor (1-2 extra type 2/3 slots) -&nbsp;Raid quality gear-2 or more type 2/3/(type 9 slots is DON). Most of this gear is already NO Drop/Trade/attunable/level recomended/required&nbsp;so it wont unbalance most bazaar gear. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>Most players&nbsp;progress from newbie gear-new cultural journeyman {(15-20) as high as 30}, expert (35-40), old cultural (recomended 45), master (55-60) or Velious (45-60), OOW/GOD (60+???) or grandmaster (65-70) or DON (60-70) with RAID gear anywhere from&nbsp;46 onward <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0>. There is ALOT of gear in EVERQUEST, this is just a sample progression path for gear. This excludes alot of normal, dropped-sellable gear from mobs or player crafted<img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0></FONT></P>
<OL>
<LI>Allow points to function at any camp, regardless of how many points at that camp a player has earned in the past. If I've ground out 1492 points in BB, I should be permitted to spend the points anywhere. The current system is roughly analogous to a store like Walmart having seperate gift certificates for each department or for each store: "Oh, I'm sorry, you can't use your $300 Toys Gift Card, because this is the Furniture Department!" "Nope, that gift card is only valid in the store where you bought it. Sorry." Silly in the extreme. </LI></OL>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>AGREE, there are only 2 factions for DON, good/evil both sell similar gear.<BR></FONT><BR>If the Wayfarer's Brotherhood is a monolithic entity, then by definition, there should be ONE favor journal, and ONE record of points earned, and ONE pool of points from which to draw. Allow the user to continue to see how many points they've earned in each camp, but regardless of how many points they've earned in Sro, if they've gotten enough work done in the BB camp, they should be able to buy the big toys anywhere they go. If someone helps you (gives you a jump) in one place (a parking garage), do you refuse to help them in a different place (a restaurant parking lot), for an equal favor (giving you a jump), because they've not helped you in the SAME place(the restaurant parking lot)?<BR></P>
<OL>
<LI>Allow players to purchase "Favor Coupons" with a 100% sellback value from adventure merchants. These are used to broker points between players - allowing a player to earn LDoN points and then transfer them to others. This allows the Wayfarer's Brotherhood to accept point transfers to others for those truly selfless paladins who want to help their guild or friends. Simply color code them, and then note in the description of each item how much they are worth. (Red: 10 Favor, Orange: 50 Favor, Yellow: 100 Favor... and so on) These must NOT be LORE - the ability to buy multiple coupons and transfer them on the open market will open LDoN up to those who are willing to do so.<BR></LI>
<LI>Expand the available gear to include new effect-possessing items (particularly those with clickable effects) Examples: various wands, clickable rings or amulets. Items with charges (wands, staves, scrolls) could be included, provided a means to recharge them was also provided (plat-purchaseable single-use mana batteries from magus, used in a point-purchaseable and reusable LDoN recharging container invented by Al'Kabor). Low level items might have smaller effects, longer recasts, fewer charges, and so forth, and purchasing these items might require a trip to visit a WB member in the WB "Outlet Store" in Natimbi or Abyssmal Sea.<BR></LI>
<LI>(Total Overhaul) Implement a different mission definition system that better typifies "mercenary work" for the WB. For randomized missions, I'm told the Anarchy Online system was pretty good. I've not seen it, and I make no such assertions. I note, however, that allowing users to set their own adventure criteria (Not just goal, but also mob density, terrain constriction, mob difficulty level, locked doors and traps, and so on) and see how this scales their point rewards (up AND down) would allow people to better customize their experience to their desires for both challenge and reward (xp, points, drops, cash). </LI></OL>
<P><FONT color=#ffff00>I've read that the South Ro/Guk missions are much harder than all the other LDON's so a 20-40 % increase in points awards is justified.</FONT><BR><BR>The more open (less confined) the space, the lower the reward. The easier (lower level average) the foes, the less the reward. The lower level the foes, the less the reward. The more locked doors (so long as there's always a long way around them) and traps the higher the reward. The tighter-packed the foes are, the more points you earn, and so on. Want a nightmare mission at the far reaches of character ability, and with uber rewards? Let them have it - and&nbsp;make them weep and beg for rezzes. Want a laid back mission for 6 level 15 wizards that are all pretty new to the game, but who don't care so much about loot or points? Let them have a good time chatting with friends and kiting sparse mobs of lower difficulty in mostly open caverns, and pay them less for each mission.<BR><BR>Let the player define their desired reward, and let the desired reward define the mission challenges. Let the player define the challenges, and let the challenges define the reward.<BR></P>
<P>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Allow the transfer of Tribute points to LDoN points, and vice versa, and allow their unlimited expenditure as with #4 above. This gives both systems an additional use, and ties them together. It does run the drawback of requiring additional oversight for "Tributed lure exploits" that garner inordinate amounts of tribute, however. </P>
<P>DON faction tokens/crystals would be better than tribute, easier to set trade in values 1example:100 LDONpts= 1 token or crystal) since that is where most people would go next after doing LDONs.</P><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
