<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&message.id=136506#M136506">37</a> of 75
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 279 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
NamelessArchon wrote:<BR>
<P>First, let's lay out the problems I see with the LDoN expansion: </P>
<P>1. Point awards are stingy in the extreme. A new player (15-20) doing LDoN adventures will be rewarded with one or two (1 or 2) points, half that if they take 120 minutes instead of 90. A level 65 player will receive ~50. At this rate, the level 65 player will require 200+ missions to purchase their 1492 gear. (1492points * 7items = 10444points for all items, 10444points / 50points per adventure = 209 adventures) The level 15 neophyte will long have outlevelled the gear they were desiring to purchase before they can afford it - this is particularly true of spells.</P>
<P>Please note that this does NOT include any augmentations, or any equipment for any non-visable slots. This is only for (head, robe, legs, arms, wrists (x2), hands) and does not include LDoN shoulders, rings, ears, belts, and so forth. This is approximately 30 (thirty) adventures to get ONE piece of gear, and assumes NO failures or partial failures (120 minute adventures).</P>
<P><FONT color=#ff9966>Agreed, points awarded are much too low.&nbsp; I started my DE-Cleric alt in LDoNs at level 20, and have done almost all my levelling there.&nbsp; Other than two missions done in Rujarkian Hills (EC camp), all the missions were done in Mistmore Catacombs (BB camp).&nbsp; My Cleric was level 26 before she had enough points to buy the spell "Remove Lesser Curse."&nbsp; While I think points do need to be upped across the board, the points awarded for lower-level missions are even more out-of-whack than at the higher levels.&nbsp; Zajeer posted about this and said it would be adjusted.&nbsp; It was mentioned again at the summit a while back.&nbsp; Hopefully, someone is already working on it.</FONT></P>
<P>2. Points are not tradeable. No player can accrue points for others, donate their points for friends, or purchase gear for others to use. No collectives, guilds, traders, or bargainers may benefit from repeated LDoN adventures, unless the reward is something that they themselves need. This means that LDoN gear exists completely outside the commodity/economic market of Everquest. While this might be useful for the establishment of a "baseline" set of equipment available to all, the time investment needed to acquire such a "baseline set" (see point #1) is prohibitive in the extreme.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ff9966>Personally, I would not mind seeing LDoN points become tradeable, but there is a down side.&nbsp; Making the points tradeable would open up the possibility of people buying plat with real dollars, buying LDoN points with said plat, and purchasing LDoN items while never having set foot in a LDoN instance. (Unless of course that there was still some requirement to "open-up" the inventory through actual missions, rather than points accrued from any source.)&nbsp; BTW, all No Drop items already exist completely outside the commodity/economic market, so this is nothing new.&nbsp; Trading points just becomes a way to change LDoN items from No Drop to Attunable.&nbsp; Just something to think about.</FONT></P>
<P>3. Gear is notably inferior to recent content items, including those of the (far) superior DoN task system. It was designed to be slightly "behind the curve" at the time the expansion was released (sub-elemental when fully aug'd, when elemental gear was not top of the line) and has aged very poorly in accordance with this. The gear relies on various augmentations that are usable only in LDoN equipment in order to approach anything a player would not be embarrassed to be using. </P>
<P><FONT color=#ff9966>I do not think LDoN gear should be pumped-up to compete directly with gear from DoN.&nbsp; As I understand it, DoN gear is not really attainable until well after level 50 or so.&nbsp; The LDoN gear should probably be looked at as very good equiptment to get one ready to tackle DoN, and have points awarded so players can get good LDoN gear to use from 35-50 or a little higher--then use it in DoN to earn upgrades.&nbsp; With LDoN being the older expansion, that would seem to fit the natural progression of things better.</FONT></P>
<P>How would I fix this? Pick your poisons - not all of these will work out of the box and unmodified. Do not apply all at the same time (1 and 2, for example)</P>
<P>Some ideas:<BR></P>
<OL>
<LI>Rebalance point costs. An item designed to be used by a level 20 player should cost no more than the number of points that player can accrue in three to six missions - somewhere between 3 and 18. This means that the costs for the current 1492 armor should be approximately 150 to 300 points each, and that the entire set should be available to a player that has performed between 21 and 35 missions. Please note - as above, this calculation does NOT include ANY augmentations or non-visable slots.&nbsp; <FONT color=#ff9966>While either rebalancing point costs of items or increasing points awarded would work, I would prefer to see more points awarded.&nbsp; Why?&nbsp; Simply because it would be far less work, and therefore will have a much greater chance of actually happening.</FONT></LI>
<LI>Rebalance point awards. Simply multiply all current awards by a factor of six to ten. The level 65 player will receive 300 to 500 points per mission, and be able to acquire their gear as above in three to five adventures per piece. Please note, as above, this does not include any "extras", only the listed slots filled with the 1492 gear.&nbsp; <FONT color=#ff9966>While I think this is the single best thing that could happen to LDons, using one factor to multiply points awarded across the board just won't cut it!&nbsp; Doing so would assume that point scaling from level to level as it is now is correct, and points just need to be bumped up.&nbsp; Nothing could be farther from the truth.&nbsp; The scaling of points is just as out-of-whack as the amount of points awarded per win.&nbsp; The whole idea of a level 20 getting ONE point for a successful 90 minute mission is insulting, and making that 6 points doesn't change that perception one bit.&nbsp; So a level 20 should get 6 points for 90 minutes of fighting level-appropriate mobs, while a level 65 should get 300 points for fighting for 90 minutes against level-appropriate mobs?&nbsp; I don't think so!</FONT><BR></LI>
<LI>Adjust statistics of LDoN items. This would work, but could be exceedingly labor intensive - if the point is to balance LDoN risk-versus-reward ratio, however, this must be considered. In particular, augmentation slots should certainly be revisited - there are many augments that will function only in LDoN gear, and many pieces of equipment that can use primarily only LDoN augments.&nbsp; <FONT color=#ff9966>As stated above,&nbsp;I do not think LDoN gear should be pumped-up in stats to make it compete with gear from later expansions, but I do think augments and augment slots are too restrictive--not only in LDoN, but throughout all of Everquest.</FONT><BR></LI>
<LI>Allow points to function at any camp, regardless of how many points at that camp a player has earned in the past. If I've ground out 1492 points in BB, I should be permitted to spend the points anywhere. The current system is roughly analogous to a store like Walmart having seperate gift certificates for each department or for each store: "Oh, I'm sorry, you can't use your $300 Toys Gift Card, because this is the Furniture Department!" "Nope, that gift card is only valid in the store where you bought it. Sorry." Silly in the extreme. <FONT color=#ff9966>Agreed--I bet the Wayfarer's do talk to each other and probably do have a very good system of communicating from one camp to another.&nbsp; Would only make sense to be gaining favor with the entire organization, not just with some fragmented faction of the Wayfarers.&nbsp; But now, if you have been GRINDING in LDoNs, I think you ought to lose points instead of gaining them! <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-very-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0>&nbsp; After all, LDoNs are FUN--they are not grind material!</FONT><BR></LI>
<LI>If the Wayfarer's Brotherhood is a monolithic entity, then by definition, there should be ONE favor journal, and ONE record of points earned, and ONE pool of points from which to draw. Allow the user to continue to see how many points they've earned in each camp, but regardless of how many points they've earned in Sro, if they've gotten enough work done in the BB camp, they should be able to buy the big toys anywhere they go. If someone helps you (gives you a jump) in one place (a parking garage), do you refuse to help them in a different place (a restaurant parking lot), for an equal favor (giving you a jump), because they've not helped you in the SAME place(the restaurant parking lot)?<BR></LI>
<LI>Allow players to purchase "Favor Coupons" with a 100% sellback value from adventure merchants. These are used to broker points between players - allowing a player to earn LDoN points and then transfer them to others. This allows the Wayfarer's Brotherhood to accept point transfers to others for those truly selfless paladins who want to help their guild or friends. Simply color code them, and then note in the description of each item how much they are worth. (Red: 10 Favor, Orange: 50 Favor, Yellow: 100 Favor... and so on) These must NOT be LORE - the ability to buy multiple coupons and transfer them on the open market will open LDoN up to those who are willing to do so.&nbsp; <FONT color=#ff9966>I still have a problem with this idea of points tradeable for plat.&nbsp; It just doesn't work for me lore-wise.&nbsp; After all, one can not sell their reputation to another.&nbsp; LDoN points are not tangeable items like crystals or platinum pieces.&nbsp; While it would be convienent to be able to buy LDoN points, I just can't&nbsp; make it seem right in my own mind.</FONT><BR></LI>
<LI>Expand the available gear to include new effect-possessing items (particularly those with clickable effects) Examples: various wands, clickable rings or amulets. Items with charges (wands, staves, scrolls) could be included, provided a means to recharge them was also provided (plat-purchaseable single-use mana batteries from magus, used in a point-purchaseable and reusable LDoN recharging container invented by Al'Kabor). Low level items might have smaller effects, longer recasts, fewer charges, and so forth, and purchasing these items might require a trip to visit a WB member in the WB "Outlet Store" in Natimbi or Abyssmal Sea.&nbsp; <FONT color=#ff9966>I like the ideas here, but it sounds like a lot of work too.&nbsp; I will be happy if I can just get the items now available when they are still useful!</FONT><BR></LI>
<LI>(Total Overhaul) Implement a different mission definition system that better typifies "mercenary work" for the WB. For randomized missions, I'm told the Anarchy Online system was pretty good. I've not seen it, and I make no such assertions. I note, however, that allowing users to set their own adventure criteria (Not just goal, but also mob density, terrain constriction, mob difficulty level, locked doors and traps, and so on) and see how this scales their point rewards (up AND down) would allow people to better customize their experience to their desires for both challenge and reward (xp, points, drops, cash).<BR><BR>The more open (less confined) the space, the lower the reward. The easier (lower level average) the foes, the less the reward. The lower level the foes, the less the reward. The more locked doors (so long as there's always a long way around them) and traps the higher the reward. The tighter-packed the foes are, the more points you earn, and so on. Want a nightmare mission at the far reaches of character ability, and with uber rewards? Let them have it - and&nbsp;make them weep and beg for rezzes. Want a laid back mission for 6 level 15 wizards that are all pretty new to the game, but who don't care so much about loot or points? Let them have a good time chatting with friends and kiting sparse mobs of lower difficulty in mostly open caverns, and pay them less for each mission.<BR><BR>Let the player define their desired reward, and let the desired reward define the mission challenges. Let the player define the challenges, and let the challenges define the reward.&nbsp; <FONT color=#ff9966>Good ideas, but I just can't see the devs putting that much work into it at this point--and that would be major work for sure.</FONT><BR></LI>
<LI>Allow the transfer of Tribute points to LDoN points, and vice versa, and allow their unlimited expenditure as with #4 above. This gives both systems an additional use, and ties them together. It does run the drawback of requiring additional oversight for "Tributed lure exploits" that garner inordinate amounts of tribute, however.&nbsp; <FONT color=#ff9966>See tradeable/transferrable points above.</FONT></LI></OL><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>Nodyin_Dev wrote: {SNIP}The ZEM (Zone Experience Modifier) on that zone [Paludal Caverns]is currently well below what you'll find in the hot zones (to the tune of 50% in some cases).  In fact the average hitpoint level in Paludal is higher than the zone I have picked out for the level 20 crowd.  I can't see any way that you wouldn't be better served hitting the new hotspots than Paludal when you hit the appropriate level ranges.
							</div>
								
