			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=30844'>







<img src="/eq/i/icons/Races/iksar.jpg" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&message.id=136556#M136556">38</a> of 75
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 265 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<blockquote><hr>NamelessArchon wrote:<br><P>First, let's lay out the problems I see with the LDoN expansion: </P><P>1. Point awards are stingy in the extreme. A new player (15-20) doing LDoN adventures will be rewarded with one or two (1 or 2) points, half that if they take 120 minutes instead of 90. A level 65 player will receive ~50. At this rate, the level 65 player will require 200+ missions to purchase their 1492 gear. (1492points * 7items = 10444points for all items, 10444points / 50points per adventure = 209 adventures) The level 15 neophyte will long have outlevelled the gear they were desiring to purchase before they can afford it - this is particularly true of spells.</P><P>Please note that this does NOT include any augmentations, or any equipment for any non-visable slots. This is only for (head, robe, legs, arms, wrists (x2), hands) and does not include LDoN shoulders, rings, ears, belts, and so forth. This is approximately 30 (thirty) adventures to get ONE piece of gear, and assumes NO failures or partial failures (120 minute adventures).</P><P>2. Points are not tradeable. No player can accrue points for others, donate their points for friends, or purchase gear for others to use. No collectives, guilds, traders, or bargainers may benefit from repeated LDoN adventures, unless the reward is something that they themselves need. This means that LDoN gear exists completely outside the commodity/economic market of Everquest. While this might be useful for the establishment of a "baseline" set of equipment available to all, the time investment needed to acquire such a "baseline set" (see point #1) is prohibitive in the extreme.</P><P>3. Gear is notably inferior to recent content items, including those of the (far) superior DoN task system. It was designed to be slightly "behind the curve" at the time the expansion was released (sub-elemental when fully aug'd, when elemental gear was not top of the line) and has aged very poorly in accordance with this. The gear relies on various augmentations that are usable only in LDoN equipment in order to approach anything a player would not be embarrassed to be using. </P><br><br><font color=#CCCC33>Great run down of whats wrong with the points system.</font><br><br><P>How would I fix this? Pick your poisons - not all of these will work out of the box and unmodified. Do not apply all at the same time (1 and 2, for example)</P><P>Some ideas:<br></P><OL><LI>Rebalance point costs. An item designed to be used by a level 20 player should cost no more than the number of points that player can accrue in three to six missions - somewhere between 3 and 18. This means that the costs for the current 1492 armor should be approximately 150 to 300 points each, and that the entire set should be available to a player that has performed between 21 and 35 missions. Please note - as above, this calculation does NOT include ANY augmentations or non-visable slots.</LI><br><br><LI>Rebalance point awards. Simply multiply all current awards by a factor of six to ten. The level 65 player will receive 300 to 500 points per mission, and be able to acquire their gear as above in three to five adventures per piece. Please note, as above, this does not include any "extras", only the listed slots filled with the 1492 gear.</LI><br><br><font color=#CCCC33>Well I think perhaps for the lower end this should be true but for the higher end it should be a little harder to get a full set. I think 2 might be a more efficient way to fixing things. Maybe not just multiplying awards by a factor of 6 to 10. Id like to see the point spread you gain to be linear, the point cost should also be linear though slightly higher thus making it slightly more difficult to get full set as you get higher.</font><br><br><LI>Adjust statistics of LDoN items. This would work, but could be exceedingly labor intensive - if the point is to balance LDoN risk-versus-reward ratio, however, this must be considered. In particular, augmentation slots should certainly be revisited - there are many augments that will function only in LDoN gear, and many pieces of equipment that can use primarily only LDoN augments.<br></LI><br><br><font color=#CCCC33>I don't think this is necessary. As has been pointed out LDoN is a kind of gear progression path that can lead to getting into DoN not ompete with it.</font><br><br><LI>Allow points to function at any camp, regardless of how many points at that camp a player has earned in the past. If I've ground out 1492 points in BB, I should be permitted to spend the points anywhere. The current system is roughly analogous to a store like Walmart having seperate gift certificates for each department or for each store: "Oh, I'm sorry, you can't use your $300 Toys Gift Card, because this is the Furniture Department!" "Nope, that gift card is only valid in the store where you bought it. Sorry." Silly in the extreme. <br><br>If the Wayfarer's Brotherhood is a monolithic entity, then by definition, there should be ONE favor journal, and ONE record of points earned, and ONE pool of points from which to draw. Allow the user to continue to see how many points they've earned in each camp, but regardless of how many points they've earned in Sro, if they've gotten enough work done in the BB camp, they should be able to buy the big toys anywhere they go. If someone helps you (gives you a jump) in one place (a parking garage), do you refuse to help them in a different place (a restaurant parking lot), for an equal favor (giving you a jump), because they've not helped you in the SAME place(the restaurant parking lot)?<br></LI><br><br><font color=#CCCC33>Tottaly agree. The lore behind multiple pools of points is too weird. It just makes too much sense that favor carries over to each camp. However they definitely should keep the idea that you need to complete adventures in each camp to get your adventure stone maxed out. If they really want people to explore each camp don't make some camps harder than others or create real incentives to get people to do em. There are many ways to people to do the lesser explored camps, like tasks and even MMs (though I might call em Historic Missions). How neat would it to have an Historic Missions set in LDoNs?</font><br><br><LI>Allow players to purchase "Favor Coupons" with a 100% sellback value from adventure merchants. These are used to broker points between players - allowing a player to earn LDoN points and then transfer them to others. This allows the Wayfarer's Brotherhood to accept point transfers to others for those truly selfless paladins who want to help their guild or friends. Simply color code them, and then note in the description of each item how much they are worth. (Red: 10 Favor, Orange: 50 Favor, Yellow: 100 Favor... and so on) These must NOT be LORE - the ability to buy multiple coupons and transfer them on the open market will open LDoN up to those who are willing to do so.<br></LI><br><br><font color=#CCCC33>I'm still a very iffy on the idea of tradable LDoN points. LDoN is suppose to be about gaining favor with the Wayfarers, it doesn't make sense to be able to trade them to other people. Now if it were a system like DoN where you are collecting crystals it might be a different thing, but the way things are set up now I dunno if I like the idea. Now being able to buy items that are tradable to recuperate some of those useless points might be an idea. </font><br><br><LI>Expand the available gear to include new effect-possessing items (particularly those with clickable effects) Examples: various wands, clickable rings or amulets. Items with charges (wands, staves, scrolls) could be included, provided a means to recharge them was also provided (plat-purchaseable single-use mana batteries from magus, used in a point-purchaseable and reusable LDoN recharging container invented by Al'Kabor). Low level items might have smaller effects, longer recasts, fewer charges, and so forth, and purchasing these items might require a trip to visit a WB member in the WB "Outlet Store" in Natimbi or Abyssmal Sea.<br></LI><LI>(Total Overhaul) Implement a different mission definition system that better typifies "mercenary work" for the WB. For randomized missions, I'm told the Anarchy Online system was pretty good. I've not seen it, and I make no such assertions. I note, however, that allowing users to set their own adventure criteria (Not just goal, but also mob density, terrain constriction, mob difficulty level, locked doors and traps, and so on) and see how this scales their point rewards (up AND down) would allow people to better customize their experience to their desires for both challenge and reward (xp, points, drops, cash).<br><br>The more open (less confined) the space, the lower the reward. The easier (lower level average) the foes, the less the reward. The lower level the foes, the less the reward. The more locked doors (so long as there's always a long way around them) and traps the higher the reward. The tighter-packed the foes are, the more points you earn, and so on. Want a nightmare mission at the far reaches of character ability, and with uber rewards? Let them have it - and make them weep and beg for rezzes. Want a laid back mission for 6 level 15 wizards that are all pretty new to the game, but who don't care so much about loot or points? Let them have a good time chatting with friends and kiting sparse mobs of lower difficulty in mostly open caverns, and pay them less for each mission.<br><br>Let the player define their desired reward, and let the desired reward define the mission challenges. Let the player define the challenges, and let the challenges define the reward.<br></LI><br><br><font color=#CCCC33>Probably way too much work than they are willing to do for LDoN. I think what they could do is add more adventure types. They could for instance allow instead of 90 minute adventures say 2-3 hour adventures. A huge dungeon crawl, where the entire mission is about exploring to the end with a nice xp bonus at the end.<br><br>Also we kinda already have ways the players can set difficulty with easy/normal/hard though I get your saying to go even further.</font><br><br><LI>Allow the transfer of Tribute points to LDoN points, and vice versa, and allow their unlimited expenditure as with #4 above. This gives both systems an additional use, and ties them together. It does run the drawback of requiring additional oversight for "Tributed lure exploits" that garner inordinate amounts of tribute, however.</LI><br><br><font color=#CCCC33>I think perhaps LDoN could have its own tribute set. Maybe some unique tribute effects specific to LDoN to make em not just another place to get tribute from.</font><br></OL><br><hr></blockquote>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
