			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&message.id=136897#M136897">44</a> of 75
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 226 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P><FONT color=#ffff66><FONT color=#cccc00>Dharkin_02 wrote:<BR></FONT><BR></FONT><FONT color=#cccc33>Well I think perhaps for the lower end this should be true but for the higher end it should be a little harder to get a full set. I think 2 might be a more efficient way to fixing things. Maybe not just multiplying awards by a factor of 6 to 10. Id like to see the point spread you gain to be linear, the point cost should also be linear though slightly higher thus making it slightly more difficult to get full set as you get higher.</FONT><FONT color=#cccc33></FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P>I'd agree... except that at 65, it's just easier to get DoN gear, and the rewards are far better. ~40 crystals per DoN mission, x9 missions = 360 crystals, or one piece of the best gear. (About 300 minutes, or five hours, to earn this many.) So what incentive are you going to offer to people to do LDoN? If the reward isn't made -dirt- -easy-, they're going to skip it for the better rewards of DoN, and rightfully so. What motivation do I have to do LDoN at 70 besides points on my charm aug?</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P><BR><FONT color=#cccc33>I don't think this is necessary. As has been pointed out LDoN is a kind of gear progression path that can lead to getting into DoN not ompete with it.</FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I'd agree. But if the reward is inferior to raiding content in the VT/Elemental range, and inferior to DoN, why should anyone in their right minds and the 60+ level range care? Why should I do them at all, except to cherry pick some spells and augments, round up a few wins for my LDoN aug and then never go back? LDoN gear should be modified to use some of the newer&nbsp;augments, and the slot-2/slot-3 stuff needs to be looked at carefully. This gear needs to be reconsidered.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P><FONT color=#cccc33>However they definitely should keep the idea that you need to complete adventures in each camp to get your adventure stone maxed out. If they really want people to explore each camp don't make some camps harder than others or create real incentives to get people to do em. There are many ways to people to do the lesser explored camps, like tasks and even MMs (though I might call em Historic Missions). How neat would it to have an Historic Missions set in LDoNs?</FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I'd argue that by not allowing people to carry points from one set of missions that they like to a camp that they don't you're really just hurting the whole expansion. It's a purely&nbsp;artificial limitation that makes no sense in terms of lore and restricts the desire of higher level folks to go back. If the SRo camp missions (for example) are really that much worse than the rest, I'd charge that the issue is one of design, but that making a second design mistake doesn't correct the first one. Allowing people to do the missions they like and use th epoints anywhere will allow them to earn the points in the missions where they are strongest, with groups that are strong for the missions they select.</P>
<P>What practical reason is there to deny players the ability to hit the camp of their choice?</P><FONT color=#cccc33></FONT>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P><FONT color=#cccc00>I'm still a very iffy on the idea of tradable LDoN points. LDoN is suppose to be about gaining favor with the Wayfarers, it doesn't make sense to be able to trade them to other people. Now if it were a system like DoN where you are collecting crystals it might be a different thing, but the way things are set up now I dunno if I like the idea. Now being able to buy items that are tradable to recuperate some of those useless points might be an idea.</FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>See my "lore-based" example above to Prometheus. Basically, if I'm a mercenary, and I'm doing work for the WB, why in the name of Cazic-Thule should they care where I want the payments sent? We already have sellable LDoN items, that sell back for a loss. I'm simply suggesting that we need to go the extra mile and make the whole system like DoN, and allow those that have earned umpty-billion points to spend them on others if they are so inclined.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<DIV><FONT color=#cccc33></FONT>
<HR>
</DIV></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P><FONT color=#cccc00>Probably way too much work than they are willing to do for LDoN. I think what they could do is add more adventure types. They could for instance allow instead of 90 minute adventures say 2-3 hour adventures. A huge dungeon crawl, where the entire mission is about exploring to the end with a nice xp bonus at the end.<BR><BR>Also we kinda already have ways the players can set difficulty with easy/normal/hard though I get your saying to go even further.</FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I recognize that this is probably asking for more than they will implement. However, if you do not ask for the moon, you will never know if it may be possible to have it. Dream big, and expect rejection.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P><FONT color=#cccc33>I think perhaps LDoN could have its own tribute set. Maybe some unique tribute effects specific to LDoN to make em not just another place to get tribute from.</FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I'd suggest that at this point, just getting people back into the camps might be an improvement. What about purchaseable runes for 66-70 spells, or purchaseable spell scrolls (to avoid trading)?</P></BLOCKQUOTE>	
		</td></tr>
