<img src="/eq/i/icons/Races/dark_elf.jpg" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&message.id=137027#M137027">47</a> of 75
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 203 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
NamelessArchon wrote:<BR>
<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<FONT color=#ff9966>Prometheus1961 wrote:<BR></FONT><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT color=#ff9966>Agreed, points awarded are much too low.&nbsp; I started my DE-Cleric alt in LDoNs at level 20, and have done almost all my levelling there.&nbsp; Other than two missions done in Rujarkian Hills (EC camp), all the missions were done in Mistmore Catacombs (BB camp).&nbsp; My Cleric was level 26 before she had enough points to buy the spell "Remove Lesser Curse."&nbsp; While I think points do need to be upped across the board, the points awarded for lower-level missions are even more out-of-whack than at the higher levels.&nbsp; Zajeer posted about this and said it would be adjusted.&nbsp; It was mentioned again at the summit a while back.&nbsp; Hopefully, someone is already working on it.</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P>Hopefully. However, I am a realist, and a programmer, and I recognize that balance changes of this magnitude are NOT a simple undertaking that can be given to just any programmer that walks into SOE and asks for a job.</P>
<P><FONT color=#33cc00>I really wouldn't know about that.&nbsp; In fact, to most programmers, I would probably be considered a computer illiterate!<img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-very-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0></FONT></P><FONT color=#ff9966>
<P></P></FONT>
<HR>

<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P><FONT color=#ff9966>Personally, I would not mind seeing LDoN points become tradeable, but there is a down side.&nbsp; Making the points tradeable would open up the possibility of people buying plat with real dollars, buying LDoN points with said plat, and purchasing LDoN items while never having set foot in a LDoN instance. (Unless of course that there was still some requirement to "open-up" the inventory through actual missions, rather than points accrued from any source.)&nbsp; BTW, all No Drop items already exist completely outside the commodity/economic market, so this is nothing new.&nbsp; Trading points just becomes a way to change LDoN items from No Drop to Attunable.&nbsp; Just something to think about.</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P>I would be inclinde to agree.... were it not for the point that DoN items are tradeable, by the exchange of crystals. Sure, there's an element of loss when moving from Crystals-&gt;Items-&gt;Crystals-&gt;Items over and over, but the items are effectively tradeable. Why this should not be the case for LDoN is a mystery to me - the items are inferior to all but the lowest end DoN equipment. Allowing them to be tradeable puts a decay factor in place for traded items, by decaying the "crystals" given back by repeated trades.</P>
<P><FONT color=#33cc00>I'm really not against the idea of tradeable points, as long as it is done in such a way as not to be exploitable.&nbsp; Neebat had what I thought to be a good idea.&nbsp; &nbsp;Neebat wrote: <FONT color=#cccccc>OR They could make one kind of points, which are camp neutral and do nothing to change your standing with any camp. You still have to build your reputation with the camp to get access to powerful items, but once you do, you can buy enough points from another player to buy and entire suit of 1400 pt armor.</FONT><BR></FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P><FONT color=#ff9966>I&nbsp;do not think LDoN gear should be pumped-up to compete directly with gear from DoN.&nbsp; As I understand it, DoN gear is not really attainable until well after level 50 or so.&nbsp; The LDoN gear should probably be looked at as very good equiptment to get one ready to tackle DoN, and have points awarded so players can get good LDoN gear to use from 35-50 or a little higher--then use it in DoN to earn upgrades.&nbsp; With LDoN being the older expansion, that would seem to fit the natural progression of things better.</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P>The problem with this is that I'm not really suggesting DoN = LDoN. More accurately, it should be a viable option to get ready for DoN - perhaps VT/Subelemental&nbsp;level gear that's relatively easy to acquire. Currently, it would be faster for my guild to raid VT and get fully Elemental flagged than to get fully aug'd sets fo LDoN gear, and we'd be better off having done so - if we could muster the raid force to do so, we'd already have done so.</P>
<P><FONT color=#33cc00>I think where most of our disagreements are coming from is the fact we are viewing this from two very different perspectives.&nbsp; You are viewing the changes&nbsp;from the perspective of a level 65-70 player.&nbsp; The changes being made, according to Zajeer, are to benefit level 20-40 players.&nbsp; My view of these changes comes from the perspective of a 20-50 level player.&nbsp; Now I admit I know little of DoN, so correct me if I am wrong, but it was my belief that players post lvl 50--or for sure post lvl 60--could move on into DoN and start to get gear there.&nbsp; I did not think a level 65-70 player would need gear from LDoN to get ready for DoN--in fact, I always thought that by the time a player was level 65+ that they were most likely already&nbsp;into DoN, or were getting gear from GoD.&nbsp; </FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><FONT color=#ff9966>While either rebalancing point costs of items or increasing points awarded would work, I would prefer to see more points awarded.&nbsp; Why?&nbsp; Simply because it would be far less work, and therefore will have a much greater chance of actually happening.</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P>I am a realist, and I recognize that this is the lesser solution when compared to simply altering point rewards. However, you'll note that I included a wide variety of potential solutions, including some that would radically reshape this old content (option 7). The point was not to present merely the "best" solution as I see it, but to allow the developers to consider ALL of the possibilities. In the end, it's not my decision, it is up to them to implement.</P>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P><FONT color=#ff9966>While I think this is the single best thing that could happen to LDons, using one factor to multiply points awarded across the board just won't cut it!&nbsp; Doing so would assume that point scaling from level to level as it is now is correct, and points just need to be bumped up.&nbsp; Nothing could be farther from the truth.&nbsp; The scaling of points is just as out-of-whack as the amount of points awarded per win.&nbsp; The whole idea of a level 20 getting ONE point for a successful 90 minute mission is insulting, and making that 6 points doesn't change that perception one bit.&nbsp; So a level 20 should get 6 points for 90 minutes of fighting level-appropriate mobs, while a level 65 should get 300 points for fighting for 90 minutes against level-appropriate mobs?&nbsp; I don't think so!</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P>Yes, that's exactly what I do mean - <U>provided that a level 20 can get a piece of level 20 appropriate gear at 30 points</U>. If this isn't the case, then the example falls through. If the level 65 is intended to earn 300 points per adventure (1500 points, per 5 adventures, enough to purchase&nbsp;one "1492 item") then I would expect that a player who is earning 6 points per adventure would be able to buy a piece of level appropriate equipment at 30 points (five adventures). This is a linear relationship, and I have assumed that the gear was balanced accordingly. If we assume the level 20 player will require 45 points per piece of equipment, then either the level 20 equipment must be adjusted, or the level 20 points must scale non-linearly, or there must be another adjustment made somewhere to compensate.</P>
<P><FONT color=#33cc00>Okay, the big problem here is that a level 20 won't be level 20 after completing 5 missions.&nbsp; They will be pushing very hard on lvl 23 by the time they do five missions.&nbsp; There is no way a player could use points to buy lvl 20 gear, because they would be lvl 30 before they even completed the set of visible items.&nbsp; Besides which, with the newbie quests from PoK, the level 20 will already have gear as good or better than most all 20 to 30 point items in LDoN.&nbsp; The lowest level LDoN gear will not be sold--no one will buy it.&nbsp; It is a moot point.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#33cc00>You said yourself that LDoN gear is not on par with DoN gear, or EP gear.&nbsp; I would also assume that it is not nearly as good as items that can be had by single groups in GoD either.&nbsp; If it is not as good, then there is no way that someone who can get gear from the other places--meaning those high level enough to go to these other places--will come to LDoN and get inferior gear.&nbsp; If the gear is now inferior for those levels, they will not use it.&nbsp; Perhaps that is why Zajeer said he might take a look at post 50 LDoNs, but his plan is for those levels 20-40.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#33cc00>As for me, I see LDoNs as a place to level 20-50 or so, and to use the newbie gear and whatever drops I might be lucky enough to get, most likely supplemented with an occasional bazaar item (hey, you have to use your plat for something!).&nbsp; My adventurer's points would be saved to buy the high-end LDoN gear, before leaving LDoN for more challenging content.&nbsp; As the gear is not as good, I can see no problem that would be caused if a person started levelling in LDoN at level 20, levelled almost exclusively in LDoNs, and by the time that player was level 50--or 55 at the latest--they could have a full set of visible LDoN 1492 armor (not including augs--visible pieces only).&nbsp; It would also be nice if the cost of the armor pieces scaled as well--after all, one bracer should not cost as much as a breastplate that has more than double the stats of the bracer.&nbsp; If this were scaled correctly, I could see a player starting at 20 and being able to buy&nbsp;gauntlets by the time they reach lvl 30.&nbsp;&nbsp;Boots by 35.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sleeves and one bracer by 40.&nbsp; Helm and one bracer by 45.&nbsp; Greaves by 50.&nbsp; Breastplate by 55.&nbsp; Going through 35 levels in LDoN should reward one with a full visible set of the 1492 armor, so that at 55 they have something good enough to actually use in the content they will be headed for.&nbsp; LDoN items are No Drop, so should have good stats for the level using it.</FONT></P><FONT color=#ff9966>
<P></P></FONT>
<HR>

<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P>As stated above,&nbsp;I do not think LDoN gear should be pumped-up in stats to make it compete with gear from later expansions, but I do think augments and augment slots are too restrictive--not only in LDoN, but throughout all of Everquest.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P>I would disagree with the latter part of this statement, but the former part I regard as being beyond question. There are Type 2 and Type 3 augments ONLY within LDoN, and nothing OUTSIDE LDoN uses them. Nothing else is so restricted, with the exception of DoN tradeskilled armors/augments. Comparing the&nbsp;whole of LDoN slot-restricted items to the best of DoN seems a bit laughable.</P>
<P><FONT color=#33cc00>The reason I said all augs are more restricted than necessary is because I do not see the need for any restriction beyond slot type and level requirements.&nbsp; Some augs are not only restricted by level and aug slot type, but have additional restrictions, like neck, wrist, back items only.</FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P><FONT color=#ff9966>I still have a problem with this idea of points tradeable for plat.&nbsp; It just doesn't work for me lore-wise.&nbsp; After all, one can not sell their reputation to another.&nbsp; LDoN points are not tangeable items like crystals or platinum pieces.&nbsp; While it would be convienent to be able to buy LDoN points, I just can't&nbsp; make it seem right in my own mind.</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P><EM><FONT color=#ccff99>WB Merchant: "Thank you Nirruden! Your selfless example of action on behalf of the Brotherhood is beyond reproach! How can we reward you?"</FONT></EM></P>
<P><EM>Nirruden CorpseSlaver, Evil necro: "<FONT color=#ccffff>Give my faithful&nbsp;apprentice the reward in my stead. He's been useful, even if he is a little new. Pity my last&nbsp;one was killed so messily when he refused to hold my foes at bay."</FONT></EM></P>
<P><EM><FONT color=#ccff99>WB Merchant: "Of course! Now,&nbsp;Apprentice OggnogginTheWicked, how about a nice shield?"</FONT></EM></P>
<P>That's lore at work there. Why, if they're going to pay ME for mercenary work (and that's even what THEY call it) should they not be willing to make a donation to someone else in my name? If I tell them to give the money/favor/items to someone, what harm does it bring to them? Either the WB&nbsp;owe me, or they don't.</P>
<P>I'm no paladin.&nbsp;Quit with the platitudes&nbsp;and pay up before Oggnoggin and I&nbsp;get violent.</P>
<P><FONT color=#33cc00>Okay, I could go for that lore-wise.&nbsp; Add Neebats suggestion stated above, and I guess I could be okay with tradeable points.</FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE dir=ltr>
<P><FONT color=#ff9966>I like the ideas here, but it sounds like a lot of work too.&nbsp; I will be happy if I can just get the items now available when they are still useful!</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P>Clickies in LDoN that are slightly inferior (cast time, recast, lower effect) to VT+ raid-acquired clickies would probably still do pretty well, I think. Poll the users and see what they think, devs.</P></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>Nodyin_Dev wrote: {SNIP}The ZEM (Zone Experience Modifier) on that zone [Paludal Caverns]is currently well below what you'll find in the hot zones (to the tune of 50% in some cases).  In fact the average hitpoint level in Paludal is higher than the zone I have picked out for the level 20 crowd.  I can't see any way that you wouldn't be better served hitting the new hotspots than Paludal when you hit the appropriate level ranges.
							</div>
								
